exo_lightning_msci_project:
- MSci Project folder containing the model, simulation output and Jupyter notebooks for data analysis 

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

initial:
- Preliminary runs of the 1D model from Aglyamov et al. (2021) https://doi.org/10.1029/2020JE006504
- Iris practice & visualising Earth data within package
- Loading and analysing some data from Sergeev et al. (2025) https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15190801

m09_air_temperature:
- Loading and analysing data from Sergeev et al. (2025) https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15190801 (microphysics-based scheme)
- Loading and analysing data from Sergeev et al. (2022) https://ckan.emac.gsfc.nasa.gov/organization/thai

model_comparison:
- Loading and analysing my simulation data output from src_original, src_onebar, src_scaled_ISA and src_odhuba

pr92_air_temperature:
- Loading and analysing data from Sergeev et al. (2025) https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15190801 (cloud-top height scheme)

src_original:
- 1D plume model
- Varying surface pressures
- Constant surface temperature
- Original stratospheric temperature function (temp_strat in plume_model.py)
- Simulation data output in "data" and "figures"

src_onebar:
- 1D plume model
- Same configurations as in Aglyamov et al. (2021) with improved conciseness and useability thanks to Dr Denis Sergeev
- Varying surface temperatures
- Constant surface pressure
- Simulation data output in "data" and "figures"

src_scaled_ISA:
- 1D plume model
- Varying surface pressures
- Constant surface temperature
- Dimensionless stratospheric temperature function (temp_strat in plume_model.py)
- Simulation data output in "data" and "figures"

src_odhuba:
- 1D plume model
- Varying surface pressures
- Constant surface temperature
- My updated stratospheric temperature function (temp_strat in plume_model.py)
- Simulation data output in "data" and "figures"
